We need to SAVE the GREENBELT! 

Which is under attack by Premier Doug Ford, who has broken his campaign promise.
Ford is opening up about 7,400 acres of land to developers for destructive urban sprawl! 

The Greenbelt:

🌱prevents and reduces soil & erosion

🌱cleans the water we drink

🌱purifies the air we breathe

🌱provides habitat for thousands of animals

🌱helps moderate temperature

🌱increases biodiversity

🌱reduces stress

There is more than enough land within existing cities and towns to build the homes we need, especially if we build compact, public transit-friendly homes. There is no need to develop and in the Greenbelt.

Stripping these 7,400 acres of protection at the request of land speculators would deny farmers the certainty they need to continue stewarding the forests, wetlands, and soils on their land.

The Greenbelt protects a lot of lands that are under pressure for development. Replacing it with land that cannot be developed and destroys the Greenbelt’s role in protecting at-risk land. 

Visit the link in my bio to sign a petition from @envirodefence to local MPPs and tell Premier Ford #HandOffTheGreenbelt!

It's the season for gift giving, and before you grab the paper roll - listen to this: every year, roughly 540,000 tonnes of gift wrap, bags and ribbons end up in landfills. Environmental journalist @candicebatista stopped by to show us some eco-friendly wrapping ideas - swipe through to check them out and click the link in our bio for the full segment!

SLIDE 1 & 2: Paper recommendations 
- Brown paper is the best, it can be recycled or even composted.
- you can get kids involved by having them attach crayons to the brown paper bag.
- they can also decorate the brown paper by adding on some cedar and drawing ornaments.

SLIDE 3 & 4: Leave the wrapping off altogether 
- A great gift is a DIY cleaning kit.
- Beeswax wraps also make the perfect gift and the perfect wrapping paper too.

SLIDE 5: Gift tags
- Make your own using old cardboard.
- You can also use these as ornaments on your tree.

PLEASE TAKE 30 SECONDS TO EMAIL YOUR MPP! LINK IN BIO!

It is infuriating how grocery stores are contributing to the profits of the fossil fuel industry by excessively wrapping every product in plastic. 
It’s unnecessary and wasteful, as seen with bananas wrapped in plastic and trays of clementines covered in plastic despite already being packaged. 
According to a recent study by @envirodefence , 71% of produce, 76% of baby food, 66% of pet food, and a staggering 64% of all surveyed products in 54 Canadian grocery stores were packaged in non-recyclable plastic.
 This is concerning, as most of this packaging ends up in landfills, incinerators, or the environment.
We need to send a clear message to our governments and grocers to take action. We demand a ban on unrecyclable plastic packaging, mandatory reuse and refill options at all stores, an end to plastic packaging for foods marketed to babies and toddlers, and high targets for safe and environmentally sound plastic recycling. 
Check out the link in our bio to take action. Let’s make a difference!
#BreakFreeFromPlastic #GroceryStore #RidiculousPackaging #SingleUsePlastic #ZeroWaste #PrioritizeReuse #ad #sponsored

It's time for Trash Talk. 

DYK that food waste and climate change are directly linked? When you throw food in your garbage can, you are part of the problem. 

Here are my top tips for reducing food waste. 

Keep your fridge tidy, clearly labeled, and stacked to prevent forgetting food items and reduce waste. Consider plastic-free alternatives for better food storage.

Prioritize plastic-free storage options such as glass jars, beeswax wraps, silicone, stainless steel, or bamboo to maintain the freshness and safety of food.

Learn how to preserve food. Techniques include freezing, pickling, fermenting, dehydrating, canning, juicing, and curing.

Purchase food items close to their sell-by dates or "ugly" produce that is often discounted but still perfectly fine.

Make the most out of ingredients by using them in their entirety or across multiple meals.

Repurpose food scraps creatively in various dishes instead of throwing them away.

Compost Everything you can! 
  To help us reduce food waste @cecnorthamerica has developed the

 FOOD MATTERS ACTION KIT, it's loaded with informative resources and hands-on, creative activities to inspire youth of all ages to prevent food waste at home, at school and in their communities.

Do you have a favourite DIY cleaning recipe? Mine is this easy and cheap All Purpose Cleaner.

Ingredients

1 cup distilled water
1 tablespoon unscented liquid castile soap
10 drops of essential oil — you can use lavender on its own or you can 5 drops of lavender and 5 drops of tea tree — both of these essential oils offer antimicrobial and anti-fungal properties — which make them great for cleaning

Instructions

Add all the ingredients to a spray bottle. Use as you would any all-purpose cleaner.
 #ecocleaning #zerowaste #cleaninghacks

Did you know that Canada’s oil and gas industry is leading the pack in pumping out pollution? Yeah, the emissions from this sector are on the rise, and it’s a real problem for climate change. 

We seriously need to put a cap on these emissions – and fast. Most folks around here agree that we should limit the pollution from oil and gas. 

But guess what? The industry’s big players are doing everything possible to slow down or water down any caps to keep their profits high.

It’s high time we tell the folks in charge that we can’t let this slide. We’ve got to get our voices heard and make sure the Canadian government limits this pollution, like now. If we don’t get tough and ambitious with these caps, there’s no way Canada can hit its goals for cutting down greenhouse gases. 
Let’s not let Big Oil call the shots anymore. 

Go to the link in my bio to sign the letter and take action now!

Hi, I’m @CandiceBatista, and I’ve been helping people live more sustainably for 25+ years. I am excited to partner with @cangeo during the final #LiveNetZero challenge. I will be sharing some of my favorite sustainable living tips with you. 

First up, easy ways to reduce food waste. 

Food waste significantly affects the planet by depleting resources like water, energy, and land and contributes to greenhouse gas emissions when wasted food decomposes in landfills, producing methane. Additionally, food waste leads to biodiversity loss due to agricultural expansion and represents a substantial economic loss. Proper food storage combats these issues by extending food’s shelf life, preserving its nutritional value, preventing contamination, and promoting mindful consumption. By storing food correctly, we can reduce waste, conserve resources, minimize environmental impact, and contribute to a more sustainable food system. 

Be on the lookout for my new book, SUSTAINED, coming February 2024.
